                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="10283" author="matthew.payne" created="Thu, 1 Apr 2004 06:45:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Would love to see something done here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It would be nice to have a light weight/plugable validator.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I frequently see the need to validate an ramdom object against some type of declartive(xml?) setting. &lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;For some favor XWork&apos;s (&lt;a href=&quot;http://opensymphony.com/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://opensymphony.com/&lt;/a&gt;) validator is very nice to work with.  &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16203" author="robh" created="Thu, 26 Jan 2006 20:27:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have moved this into the timeframe of 2.1 but it is definitely on the radar. AleksS and I have been working on a Java/.NET expression language that can then be used as the basis of a validation language (which Aleks has already prototyped for .NET). StevenD has been doing some interesting work on Valang and JanM is doing some interesting work in the rules area so there is certainly a lot to go at here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Rob&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20625" author="devijvers" created="Thu, 2 Nov 2006 23:58:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;UriB is involved in the JSR-303 spec. It&apos;s still early days for this one but I think it would be a good candidate too.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="24938" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Fri, 20 Jul 2007 21:01:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Moving this to 3.0 M1, since we are unlikely to tackle this within the 2.x branch. 3.0 will also allow this to require Java 5 (without any constraints).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="45266" author="fenrir" created="Sat, 4 Jul 2009 19:53:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I would like to have &apos;validation&apos; namespace for declaring validation in Spring context.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
